<main class="page">
  <h1>Request scope</h1>
  <p class="lead">Two per-request accessors. <code>cookies()</code> reads the request's <code>Bun.CookieMap</code>; <code>context()</code> is a free-form carrier bag handed from middleware to handler. Each is shown on its own below.</p>

  <p><code>cookies()</code> reads the request cookie jar. The browser sets <code>document.cookie</code>, then the RPC reads it back server-side — the value round-trips through the request scope.</p>
  <Demo id="cookies" title="cookies()" server="src/server/rpc/platformCookies.ts" client="src/ui/demos/platform/CookiesDemo.abide" tab="server">
    <CookiesDemo />
  </Demo>

  <p><code>context()</code> is the per-request carrier bag. A per-RPC middleware writes into it; the handler beneath it in the onion reads it back — the hand-off from a middleware layer to the handler.</p>
  <Demo id="context" title="context()" server="src/server/rpc/platformContext.ts" client="src/ui/demos/platform/ContextDemo.abide" tab="server">
    <ContextDemo />
  </Demo>

  <p>A per-RPC <code>middleware</code> array composes an onion around the handler. The first layer <em>authorizes</em>: it either returns an <code>error(403)</code> Response to short-circuit (the handler never runs), or calls <code>next()</code> and lets the second layer run. Both calls hit the real router pipeline in the browser:</p>

  <Demo id="guard" title="RPC <code>middleware</code> — onion + short-circuit" server="src/server/rpc/platformGuard.ts" client="src/ui/demos/platform/GuardDemo.abide" tab="server">
    <GuardDemo />
  </Demo>
</main>
